Tariffs raise government revenue by taxing domestic consumption of foreign goods and services. They should therefore permit reduction of other forms of domestic revenue raising ('income tax!'). 
Their primary incentive effect is substitution in favor of domestic production. 
Unwelcome collateral economic effects are inflation, and inefficiency through disruption of the international division of labor. 
They also have political implications, both positive (as diplomatic tools) and negative (as sources of international friction). 
Given all of this (and of course more), simple libertarian hostility seems even less nuanced than simple nationalist enthusiasm. Cautious experimental interest is the soundest take.
